This is a simple implementation of the login server needed by the
Google Drive KODI Addon at https://github.com/cguZZman/plugin.googledrive

I wrote this because I couldn't get his official server code to compile
(from here https://github.com/cguZZman/drive-login ).

This other one works, but it uses some older javascript libraries and
I didn't want to have to rely on something that's always going out of
date (https://github.com/aldacco/drive-login/ ).

This server's only dependency is OpenSSL. If you've got a C compiler
installed you can build it just by typing "make".

To run it you'll first need to setup your Google OAuth 2.0 credentials,
just like for those other servers. Follow the setup instructions on the
aldacco repo.

After you obtain the credentials, set them in two environment variables

  export GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=..client id..
  export GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=..client secret..

Then run with
  ./kodilogin -h localhost

It listens on port 3000 by default, so you'll need to enable
  http://localhost:3000
as the redirect URI for this google client.

If you want to run it on a public address, Google will require you to have
a valid DNS name, it will require https. So you're going to need to get 
your own server certificate and key. Once you have those, you can set them
using -C to set the CA certificate file, -c for the server certificate file,
-k for the server private key file.

If you want to bind the listener to a specific address use -a, otherwise
it will listen on all available network interfaces.

So you might invoke as
  ./kodilogin -h www.example.com -p 8000 -C cacert.pem -c servercert.pem -k serverkey.pem

